2. How This Changes the Inference Code
Since the patient data is handed to the backend on a silver platter, your colleague's job
in the healthylabs-inference repo actually becomes cleaner, but the logic shifts
slightly.
A. orchestrator/self_rag_router.py (The Brain)
When the LLM decides on a retrieval strategy, it now has instant access to the patient's
context.
• The Change: The router will embed the user's query_text alongside their
known_conditions. For example, instead of just searching Neo4j for "ibuprofen
side effects", the router will intelligently expand the query to search Neo4j for:
"Ibuprofen side effects AND contraindications for Hypertension AND interaction
with Lisinopril."
B. retrieval/kg_overrides.py (The Safety Net)
Previously, we assumed this module would have to hunt down the patient in the
database. Now, it uses the frontend data to perform Targeted Graph Lookups.
• The Change: If your Knowledge Graph (Neo4j) contains general medical facts
(like Drug-Drug interactions or Drug-Condition contraindications), your
colleague will write Cypher queries that take the frontend array
(["Lisinopril", "Ibuprofen"]) and ask the graph: "Do any of these drugs
conflict with each other?"
• Cypher Example for Colleague:
Cypher
// Check if the requested drug (Ibuprofen) interacts with any of the
frontend-provided medications
UNWIND $frontend_medications AS current_med
MATCH (d1:Drug {name: 'Ibuprofen'})-[r:INTERACTS_WITH]->(d2:Drug
{name: current_med.name})
RETURN d1.name, d2.name, r.severity, r.description
C. synthesis/conflict_resolver.py (The Final Guard)
This is where the magic happens. The resolver will take the vectors retrieved from Neo4j
(the medical guidelines) and lay them over the frontend's patient_context.
• The Logic: If a retrieved AtomicChunk from a clinical guideline says "First-line
treatment is NSAIDs," the resolver will check the patient_context, see the
"known_conditions": ["Hypertension"], and the LLM will generate a
contradiction flag because NSAIDs can elevate blood pressure.